  "signature": "ed25519:5f4b2c2a5ec9ff2bfd98054ffd069f47dd4199b5c92ee5690fc06bece0b4bdff9aa25c4e6246ba1ba9f1dd7e59fa15ced1ff804412163f6741da2b0c1b870b01",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/sqa-gradation2",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical R2022 R1 is a commercially validated FEA solver with documented V&V procedures. The FDA in-house Python post-processing scripts are version-controlled in a Git repository with unit tests covering all QoI extraction routines. DePuy Synthes provided solver verification documentation consistent with Gradation 2 SQA requirements. All three ensemble members satisfy the required SQA level for a Medium model risk application."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/code-verification-gradation2",
      "rationale": "Patch tests and benchmark problems (cantilever beam, Hertzian contact) were executed in Ansys prior to the pedicle screw simulations. Results matched analytical solutions within 0.5% for linear stiffness and 1.2% for contact pressure, confirming code correctness at Gradation 2. FDA and DePuy Synthes ensemble members performed equivalent benchmark exercises with documented pass/fail records archived in the study repository."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/discretization-error-gradation2",
      "rationale": "A systematic mesh convergence study was conducted using three mesh densities (coarse: ~45k elements, medium: ~120k elements, fine: ~310k elements) for the non-cannulated construct. Richardson extrapolation yielded a Grid Convergence Index (GCI) of 0.8% for stiffness and 1.1% for yield force on the medium mesh selected for production runs. Discretization error is bounded at <2% for all QoIs, exceeding the Gradation 2 requirement and satisfying Gradation 3 criteria."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/solver-error-gradation2",
      "rationale": "Iterative solver residuals were monitored for all nonlinear load steps; force and displacement residuals converged below 1e-4 relative tolerance. Energy balance checks confirmed <0.1% artificial energy in all simulations. Newton-Raphson convergence was achieved within 8 iterations per load step on average, with no divergence events recorded across the 11-specimen ensemble."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/use-error-gradation2",
      "rationale": "Model setup was performed by two independent analysts following a documented simulation protocol. A third analyst performed an independent review of boundary conditions, material assignments, contact definitions, and load application. Discrepancies identified during review were resolved prior to production runs. The simulation protocol is archived and version-controlled, satisfying Gradation 2 use-error requirements."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/model-form-gradation2",
      "rationale": "The FEA model uses a nonlinear implicit formulation with Ti-6Al-4V isotropic elasto-plastic material (bilinear kinematic hardening calibrated from coupon tensile tests). Cortical and cancellous bone analog (UHMWPE blocks per ASTM F1717) are modeled with linear elastic properties consistent with published values. Frictional contact (mu=0.2) is applied at screw-block interfaces. The model form captures the dominant physics of the compression-bending test and has been reviewed against the ASTM F1717 test configuration."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/model-inputs-gradation2",
      "rationale": "Material properties for Ti-6Al-4V were derived from five tensile coupon tests (mean E=114 GPa, yield=880 MPa) with documented uncertainty. UHMWPE block properties were taken from manufacturer data sheets with ±5% bounds applied in sensitivity analyses. Geometric inputs were derived from calibrated CMM measurements of the actual test specimens (n=11), with dimensional uncertainty <0.05 mm. Input uncertainty contributions were propagated using a one-at-a-time sensitivity study confirming model inputs uncertainty is <3% of total QoI uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/test-samples-gradation2",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were assembled and tested across two independent laboratories (FDA CDRH and an ISO 17025-accredited external laboratory). Specimens were drawn from the same manufacturing lot, with dimensional inspection confirming conformance to design drawings. Inter-laboratory variability in stiffness (CV=4.2%) and yield force (CV=3.8%) was within expected manufacturing tolerance, supporting sample representativeness at Gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/test-conditions-gradation2",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted at a single loading rate (5 mm/min displacement control) and ambient laboratory temperature (22±2°C) per ASTM F1717. Only one test condition was evaluated; in vivo loading rates and physiological temperature conditions were not explored. This limits the factor to Gradation 1, which falls below the required Gradation 2. This gap is documented as a known limitation of the validation dataset and is addressed through conservative acceptance bounds (<10% QoI difference) and the corroborating multi-laboratory agreement."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/input-equivalency-gradation2",
      "rationale": "FEA model inputs were systematically mapped to experimental measurements for each of the 11 test specimens. Screw geometry was taken from individual CMM measurements rather than nominal design values. Block material properties were batch-verified. Boundary conditions replicate the ASTM F1717 fixture constraints with documented fixture compliance correction applied to experimental displacement data. Input equivalency is documented in a traceability matrix archived in the study repository."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/output-comparison-gradation2",
      "rationale": "Quantitative comparison was performed using the E/uval metric per ASME V&V 40. For stiffness: E/uval=0.84 (|QoI difference|=4.1%); for yield force: E/uval=1.12 (|QoI difference|=5.8%); for force at 40 mm: E/uval=0.97 (|QoI difference|=3.2%). All three QoIs satisfy the pre-established acceptance criterion of E/uval < 1.96 and <10% difference. The structured quantitative comparison with uncertainty normalization satisfies Gradation 3 output comparison requirements."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/qoi-relevance-gradation2",
      "rationale": "The three QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are the primary mechanical performance metrics specified in ASTM F1717 and directly correspond to the COU decision criteria for pedicle screw construct adequacy. These QoIs are clinically relevant surrogates for construct integrity under physiological bending loads. The mapping from QoI to COU decision was reviewed by the credibility assessment team and documented in the COU definition."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/validation-relevance-gradation2",
      "rationale": "The validation activity directly replicates the COU: the same non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw design, the same ASTM F1717 compression-bending test configuration, and the same FEA modeling framework are used in both validation and the intended regulatory submission. The validation specimens are from the same manufacturing lot as the submission device. The gap between the single-condition validation and multi-condition clinical use is acknowledged and addressed via the conservative acceptance bounds and the documented Test conditions factor shortfall."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/decision/cou1-noncannulated-accepted",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/org/fda-cdrh-osel",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment for COU1 (non-cannulated pedicle screw compression-bending) is accepted at Medium assurance level. Twelve of thirteen V&V 40 factors meet or exceed their required gradation levels. The single shortfall — Test conditions at Gradation 1 against a required Gradation 2 — is documented, understood, and mitigated by: (1) conservative pre-established acceptance bounds (<10% QoI difference, E/uval < 1.96) that provide margin against uncharacterized condition variability; (2) multi-laboratory validation (N=11 across two ISO 17025-accredited facilities) demonstrating reproducibility; and (3) all three primary QoIs passing quantitative acceptance criteria with E/uval values of 0.84, 1.12, and 0.97 respectively, well below the 1.96 threshold. The FEA ensemble (FDA, Ansys, DePuy Synthes) demonstrates consistent predictive performance across all QoIs. Software quality assurance, numerical code verification, mesh convergence, and use-error controls all satisfy Gradation 2 or higher requirements. The overall evidence body supports the conclusion that the FEA modeling framework is credible for its intended use in supporting regulatory decision-making for this device design, and the Accepted decision is appropriate for a Class II, Medium model risk, Medium consequence application.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
